t2m
---

Converts text to morse (raw audio).

Run as:

	$ echo 'Hello, world!' | ./t2m | aplay -r 44100 -f S16_LE

To generate an OGG file:

	$ echo 'Hello, world!' | ./t2m -c 0.8 | oggenc -r -C 1 -o foo.ogg -

	(Capping the volume reduces clipping in the encoded OGG file.)

To morse interactively:

	$ ( stty raw; stty isig; trap 'stty -raw' INT; ./t2m | aplay -r 44100 -f S16_LE >/dev/null 2>&1 )

	(Quit using ^C.)


morsetrainer
------------

A learning program, Koch Method. It uses t2m and aplay to generate
sound and ncurses for its user interface. It's best to run it in a
terminal with a big font. The following command also extends $PATH in
case you don't want to install the programs:

	$ xterm -fa 'DejaVu Sans Mono:pixelsize=46' \
		-e bash -c 'PATH=$PATH:~/work/C/morsetools morsetrainer -l 6; read'

This starts the tool in level 6, i.e. 6 different characters. If you're
feeling comfortable, try to increase the level by one. If you're feeling
really comfortable, try to reduce the "grace time": "-g 1.25" is default
which waits for 125% of a character's length after it has been sent. In
reality, there is no grace time ("-g 0"). You can also increase the
number of words per minute. Default is "-w 20".


morsetrainer2
-------------

A learning program for intermediates. "morsetrainer" is meant to teach
you single characters. In time, though, you want to learn to understand
words and sentences. This is where "morsetrainer2" comes in: A series of
characters separated by spaces is sent and you have to write them all
down. This is not an interactive process: You can write them down by
hand and, after the transmission is over, then enter them into your
computer.

By default, "morsetrainer2" sends a "CQ CQ CQ" before the actual
transmission starts. This is meant to help you picking up the rhythm.
